Optimizing Urban Logistics: Vehicle Routing
Problem With Underground Transportation
Ho Young Jeong
 and Byung Duk Song
Abstract— In response to increasing congestion and ineffi-
ciencies in urban freight transportation systems, driven by the
rapid rise of e-commerce and urbanization, underground logistics
are emerging as a promising alternative.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
This study introduces
the Vehicle Routing Problem with Underground Transportation
(VRP-UT), a novel model that integrates traditional vehicle
routing with underground logistics facilities to optimize urban
deliveries.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
To address the model’s complexity, we propose a
hybrid solution approach that combines Q-learning with prun-
ing techniques, enhancing route optimization and minimizing
unnecessary operations.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
Comprehensive numerical and sensitivity
analyses further validate the model’s effectiveness, positioning
VRP-UT as a scalable and efficient solution to meet growing
urban logistics demands while supporting sustainable develop-
ment.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
Index Terms— Urban logistics, urban congestion manage-
ment, last-mile delivery, vehicle routing, mathematical model,
metaheuristic.
items.label: Functional Requirement

Recent

large-scale urban logistics systems [71], offering valuable

Air delivery

items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
Against this backdrop, Underground Logistics Systems
(ULS) have emerged as an innovative solution, offering
numerous benefits for urban distribution.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
The ULS concept
involves using subterranean channels for logistics operations
to alleviate surface traffic congestion, reduce operational costs,
and improve delivery efficiency [60].
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
This novel approach,
which includes using underground rail resources, represents
a significant shift in urban logistics, paving the way for
more sustainable and efficient urban development.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
ULS also
aligns with sustainable urban development goals, introducing
a transformative logistics model with modular autonomous
vehicles and dynamic pickup and delivery systems [10], [52].
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
ULS sys-
tems, requiring minimal surface space, offer resilience against
extreme weather impacts on logistics, enhancing the reliability
and safety of delivery services.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
Furthermore, using ULS as a
supplementary freight delivery method can significantly ease
surface transportation burdens, reducing highway maintenance
expenses and decreasing truck-related accidents.
items.label: Functional Requirement

items.text:
Globally, the development of ULS has attracted sig-
nificant academic interest, with many countries increasingly
exploring the use of underground spaces.

L ITERATURE REVIEW
Urban development and the continuous expansion of
metropolitan areas have brought about challenges such as
traffic congestion, pollution, and space constraints, which not
only hinder the efficiency of logistics but also have significant
negative impacts on the environment and urban mobility [6],
[22].
items.label: Constraint

items.text:
Urban logistics is crucial for ensuring the timely and
cost-effective delivery of goods, yet conventional surface-level
transportation methods face limitations in addressing these
challenges [32].

and Celikoglu [24] highlights that integrating underground
logistics not only alleviates surface-level congestion but also
contributes to reducing carbon footprints.

items.text:
Minimum Spanning Tree as a Lower Limit
In addition to an upper limit, establishing a lower limit is
vital for efficient pruning in QLP.
items.label: Constraint

items.text:
The MST represents the
minimal route cost required to connect all nodes, helping QLP
identify when extending a route is unproductive and should be
pruned.
items.label: Constraint

items.text:
Pruning for Optimal Transfer Efficiency
In VRP-UT with transfer constraints, pruning is essential
for reducing computational complexity by eliminating paths
that cannot contribute to an optimal solution.
items.label: Constraint

items.text:
The primary
objective is to identify transfer scenarios that can be postponed
or avoided, enhancing routing efficiency without sacrificing
optimality.For clarity, in the following pruning conditions,
LLL denotes the minimum required time for completion of
a route segment, based on the MST lower bound.
items.label: Constraint

helping identify paths that exceed feasible cost thresholds.

completion time.
